const faqs = [
  { q: 'Do Tampa homes even need reliable heating?', a: 'Yes. Tampa sees 5 to 15 nights per year below 40 degrees and has had hard freezes in January that dropped homes below 30 inside when heating failed. Most Tampa homes run a heat pump or a heat-strip air handler, and both need annual service to stay reliable on the few nights they actually matter.' },
  { q: 'What is the difference between a heat pump and a furnace?', a: 'A heat pump uses the same refrigerant cycle as your AC, just reversed, to move warmth into the home very efficiently down to about 35 degrees ambient. Below that, most Tampa heat pumps switch on electric-resistance heat strips as backup. Furnaces (gas or propane) are rare in Florida and only used in some new-construction areas.' },
  { q: 'Why is my heat pump running but blowing cool air?', a: 'Most often: a stuck reversing valve, low refrigerant charge, a triggered defrost cycle, or heat strips that did not engage as backup. A quick diagnostic separates which one is happening. Do not run the system in emergency heat for more than a day or your electric bill will jump sharply.' },
  { q: 'How often should I service my heat pump in Florida?', a: 'Twice yearly, cooling prep in spring and heating prep in fall. The fall visit catches reversing valve issues, heat strip element failures, and defrost control problems before the first cold snap.' },
  { q: 'Can you replace my electric strips with something more efficient?', a: 'If you are on an older single-stage heat pump, upgrading to a modern variable-speed heat pump with a properly sized backup strip can cut winter heating costs 30 to 50%. We will size and quote options when you are ready.' },
  { q: 'What about heating for my Florida room or garage?', a: 'Ductless mini-splits are the best solution. They heat and cool independently of your main system, run 22+ SEER2, and handle Tampa winters easily.' },
];

