  <h2>Wesley Chapel heating: mostly heat pumps, rarely furnaces</h2>
  <p>This page covers <strong>heating services</strong> broadly, every way a Florida home makes heat. If your specific issue is a heat pump that will not heat or cool, our dedicated <a href="/services/heat-pump-repair-tampa/">heat pump repair</a> page goes deeper on that unit. Here is how heat actually gets delivered across Tampa Bay:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Heat pumps (about 85%):</strong> the same outdoor unit that cools you reverses its refrigerant flow to pull heat into the home in winter.</li>
    <li><strong>Electric heat strips (most of the rest):</strong> coil-shaped resistance heaters inside the air handler that kick in as backup or emergency heat.</li>
    <li><strong>Gas or propane furnaces (rare):</strong> found mainly in newer upscale developments.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Each type has its own failure modes, maintenance needs, and parts. Our Wesley Chapel technicians are trained on all three and our trucks carry parts for every configuration, so a single team can diagnose whatever is keeping your home cold without sending out for a specialist.</p>

  <TrustBar />

  <h2>Why Florida heating fails at the worst possible time</h2>
  <p>A heat pump cools all summer and then sits in cooling mode for months. The heating side, the reversing valve, the defrost board, the heat strips, goes untested from spring until the first genuinely cold night. That is exactly when it gets asked to work hard for the first time in eight months, and that is when hidden faults surface:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>A reversing valve</strong> that quietly stuck over summer only reveals itself when you call for heat.</li>
    <li><strong>Heat strips</strong> with a burned-out element pass unnoticed until they are the only heat source.</li>
    <li><strong>A defrost board</strong> failure shows up the first frosty morning, not before.</li>
    <li><strong>A weak capacitor</strong> that limped through cooling season finally quits under the extra winter load.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>None of these are dramatic in October. All of them are an emergency at 2am in January when the schedule is full. That predictable timing is the entire argument for a fall tune-up, and it is why we push it every year.</p>

  <h2>Heat pump heating services we provide</h2>
  <p>Since the heat pump is the heating system for most homes here, most of our winter work is on it:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Heating-mode repair:</strong> reversing valve failures, defrost control board issues, charge problems, compressor lockouts, and auxiliary-heat failures, handled with our <a href="/services/heat-pump-repair-tampa/">heat pump repair</a> team.</li>
    <li><strong>Fall tune-ups:</strong> we test reversing valve operation, the defrost sensor, the heat-strip sequencer, emergency-heat mode, and outdoor coil performance in heat mode.</li>
    <li><strong>Heat pump replacement:</strong> variable-speed units from Carrier, Trane, Lennox, and Rheem give Tampa homeowners 22+ SEER2 cooling and strong cold-weather heating, installed through our <a href="/services/hvac-installation-tampa/">HVAC installation</a> crew.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Heat strip and air handler heating</h2>
  <p>When temperatures drop below about 35 degrees, heat pumps lose efficiency and most systems switch on an electric-resistance <strong>heat strip</strong> as supplemental heat. These strips are essentially large toaster elements: simple, reliable, and expensive to run. The issues we repair most:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Sequencer failure,</strong> with strips stuck off (no heat) or stuck on (runaway bill).</li>
    <li><strong>Element burn-out,</strong> one or more coils open.</li>
    <li><strong>High-limit trips</strong> from a failed blower or a dirty filter.</li>
    <li><strong>Control-wire issues</strong> at the thermostat, often after a DIY <a href="/services/thermostat-installation-tampa/">thermostat swap</a>.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Running on emergency heat for more than a day or two spikes your bill significantly. There is almost always a fix for the underlying heat pump issue, so call before the strips become your whole heating bill.</p>

